\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Preferences and labor endowment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Continuum of individuals indexed by 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Individuals are risk-neutral with discount rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

: maximize 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=\int_{0}^{\infty}\exp(-\rho t)C(t)dt
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Individuals endowed with unit of labor, which can be supplied to final good
 production (
\begin_inset Formula $l^{F}$
\end_inset

), intermediate good production 
\begin_inset Formula $(l^{I})$
\end_inset

, and R&D (
\begin_inset Formula $l^{RD}$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Aggregate labor market satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L_{t}^{F}+L_{t}^{I}+L_{t}^{RD}=1
\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Final good technology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Consumption consists of a final good.
 Produced using labor and a continuum of intermediate goods 
\begin_inset Formula $j\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

 with production technology 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y(t)=\frac{L^{\beta}(t)}{1-\beta}\int_{0}^{1}q_{j}^{\beta}(t)k_{j}^{1-\beta}(t)dj
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}$
\end_inset

 is quality, 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{j}$
\end_inset

 is quantity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
CES production structure ensures constant markups –> tractability
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Intermediate good technology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Each good 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is produced with a linear technology 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k_{j}=\overline{q}l_{j}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{q}=\int_{0}^{1}q_{j}dj$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Assumptions guarantee that only the technology leader produces in equilbrium
 –> no limit pricing
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Research and development
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Successful R&D project on quality 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 renders its owner an incument with quality 
\begin_inset Formula $(1+\lambda)q$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Incumbent and mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{j}$
\end_inset

 of entrants work on R&D on machine 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Innovations effort 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 requires 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 units R&D labor generates innovations at Poisson rate 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
R_{I}(z_{I};\overline{z}) & = & \chi_{I}z_{I}\phi(\overline{z})\\
R_{E}(z_{E}:;\overline{z}) & = & \chi_{E}z_{E}\phi(\overline{z})
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(z)$
\end_inset

 decreasing such that 
\begin_inset Formula $z\phi(z)$
\end_inset

 is increasing, and where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{z}=\int_{0}^{m}z(l)dl+z_{I}
\]

\end_inset

is the total innovation effort in that machine line
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Incumbents are large and take into account their effect on 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{z}$
\end_inset

, but entrants are small and do not
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
An entrant can only hire 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi>0$
\end_inset

 units of R&D labor; in equilibrium, total entrant effort is 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{z}_{j}^{E}=\min(M,m)\xi$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is the mass that is present when there is free entry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Knowledge spillovers and non-competes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Individual supplying R&D labor to either an incumbent or an entrant on a
 project on quality 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 acquires the ability to spin-off and form his own R&D project at Poisson
 rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 per unit of R&D labor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Therefore, if 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{j}^{RD}$
\end_inset

 is the total amount of R&D labor used by the incumbent and entrants in
 machine line 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\dot{n}_{j} & = & \nu l_{j}^{RD}-vn_{j}\\
\dot{m}_{j} & = & vn_{j}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This means that we actually have three state variables, 
\begin_inset Formula $(q,n,m)$
\end_inset

, which is a problem.
 No way around this - will simply need to use few grid points on 
\begin_inset Formula $(q,n,m)$
\end_inset

 and interpolate.
 Should still be feasible...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
R&D race 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 becomes free entry at exogenous rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Easier model to solve: assume non-competes are permanent.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 becomes really important for fitting data (otherwise there is no entry
 in the model, just incumbents incrementally improving their quality).
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Equilibrium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Focus on recursive BGP where state variables are either constant (e.g.
 distributions, productivity-normazlied wages) or grow at constant rate
 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 (e.g.
 output, productivity, wages), and where the only aggregate state variable
 is the joint distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tilde{q},m,n)$
\end_inset

 in the economy (and where individual 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tilde{q},m,n)$
\end_inset

 is the individual state of each firm).
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{q}=q/\overline{q}$
\end_inset

, that is, it is the quality relative to the economy average.
 From now on I will simply use the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{q}$
\end_inset

 where there is no confusion.
\end_layout

